**W1-D7-Mini_Project_Library_System**
Goal: First time combining classes — one class holding a list of *other* objects. This is exactly how Django works later: Library = a database table, Book = a row/record. `add_book`, `search_book`, `remove_book` are the manual version of what Django's ORM (`.save()`, `.filter()`, `.delete()`) does for you automatically.

```python
class Book:
    def __init__(self, title, author, is_available=True):
        self.title = title
        self.author = author
        self.is_available = is_available

    def __str__(self):
        status = "Available" if self.is_available else "Borrowed"
        return f"{self.title} by {self.author} - {status}"
```

